[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Reviewing SecurityManager installation**\n\nI need to install SecurityManager, but on Java 21, it seems System.setSecurityManager is unsupported. It's terminally deprecated, yet still allowed under certain conditions. From JDK 18 onward, it throws an UnsupportedOperationException unless the system property java.security.manager is set to \"allow\". I’m curious if I can pass certain JVM arguments for tests under a native image, even though SecurityManager support might be limited there. I should also check if existing tests use a non-null SecurityManager at runtime.\n\n**Exploring SecurityManager testing**\n\nI need to consider adding a test for a custom SecurityManager with appropriate build arguments. It seems the app can start with a SecurityManager, which would make System.getSecurityManager non-null if the property is set to default. But I'm unsure if Java 21 will still allow this. For testing, I could create a JUnit test that sets a PermissiveSecurityManager and restores it afterward. Also, I should explore adding JVM arguments like \"-Djava.security.manager=allow\" for tests and check runtime arguments for the native image in build.gradle.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_056530e784eeaaea0169ef5a143ae081918740fd677ab8f093\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp71ocZDmztOKOI15h8eoSol5pwJ26TjBlqmG_-3The_2EFlSPva5IbXi789hrz0jPcF8iEupctryBo592C3CP3WM4rZ9KmCm2PKrJ-syXJB-xVwPM63p9Ef61XhCQNI77_yJj4KfqG2CvHIu7U_DEKqdXWUF_eeCpcjKaY9VaCCjr5JMqiVshdir6fjWrNUbk7o9H6zJp_eL_4-VVaPx_0Kbtn5VfG-9uN-0CTt1HeLUpyrxu-x_y1-ZJ8fjJCRD_c9u8rGh7h3jX-Na9dGTFcXvjuxP3f9m_1XoGGx53snhzQLF1vm-LTlaPNVIyPP7O_NiB6Bl2HOPfQQM6Eo9o_SNu8mNzhdwsExZ5fG9U6zMz_uby_jV7xECUQxmvykVhiqkHGPrfvFo-6nmnNJr2BRWtrgI-58r-GhVOhIFIEsY1JeGCrZfTdTNkGfx2MZEHwqUBt2qc936DzxWMN-koAL4xj92JFScjm7amVW2Kx1auU_xWsG5TtiSCapJqsaqFKMmlnITbISAZP-xlrJ9qi3g2D_CdhgblCsCP9_Y44NFG2RvaaqJQfLIaeVQ1FY6y7CvjRG